Motivation

Genetic motivation to use pedigree

  • Genetic data are non-independent

  • Uses all the information from relatives. Each relative contributes to the estimate of each individuals BV depending on how genetically close they are

  • Predict the breeding values for grandparents, parents and progeny in one step

  • More complex genetic models, such as additive, dominance, paternal and clonal effects

  • It provides a prediction even if an individual does not have a measured phenotype, as long as one or more relatives are measured

BLUP

Statistical advantages

Important points related to the BLUP are incorporated in its name:

  • B = Best means it maximizes the correlation between true and predicted breeding values or minimizes prediction error variance

  • L = Linear because predictors are linear functions of observations

  • U = Unbiased is a desired statistical propriety related to the estimation of realized values for a random variable

  • P = Prediction involves predicting the true breeding value.

Animal Model - Sommer

  • yield = response variable

  • block = fixed effect

  • id = genotype (lines) random effect

  • wheat.A = A matrix indexing the random effect (G)

library(sommer)

m1 <- mmer2(yield~ 1 + block,
                random=~g(id),
                G=list(id=as.matrix(wheat.A)),
                silent = T, data=pheno)

Animal Model - Sommer

  • Residual diagnostic
plot(m1)

Animal Model - Sommer

  • Variance component

  • Heritability

VC = summary(m1)$var.comp.table
h2 = VC[1,1]/(VC[1,1] + VC[2,1]/4)
print(h2)
